25:30.996 --> 25:35.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Judy Woodruff sat down with
Atlantic writer
Barbara Bradley Hagerty, who
spent several

25:35.667 --> 25:41.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
months looking at how presidents
who left
office at relatively young ages
decided what

25:41.106 --> 25:43.175 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to do with the rest of their
lives.

25:43.208 --> 25:46.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is part of the "NewsHour"'s
ongoing partnership
with "The Atlantic."

25:46.912 --> 25:50.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY, "The
Atlantic": Well,
generally, presidents -- and
let's refer throughout

25:50.983 --> 25:54.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
history -- unless presidents
were wealthy,
they generally had to work.

25:54.553 --> 25:58.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, George Washington became the
largest whiskey
distiller.

25:58.457 --> 26:04.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, William Howard
Taft became
the Supreme Court chief justice.

26:04.163 --> 26:05.864 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, they had to work.

26:05.898 --> 26:09.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, more recently, what I was
interested
in seeing is that presidents are
living so

26:09.735 --> 26:11.503 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
long now.

26:11.537 --> 26:16.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when a president leaves in
midlife, at
the peak of his game, what does
he do then?

26:16.542 --> 26:18.377 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What does he do for an encore?

26:18.410 --> 26:25.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, over time,
the idea of
what to do and the amount of
time has changed.

26:25.417 --> 26:27.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Take us back to modern
presidents.

26:27.753 --> 26:29.488 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, you looked at Jimmy
Carter.

26:29.521 --> 26:33.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Jimmy
Carter, he
had a rough landing after his
presidency,

26:33.759 --> 26:35.561 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
which is not atypical.

26:35.594 --> 26:43.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Jimmy Carter loses to -- in
a landslide
to Ronald Reagan, and he comes
home to Plains,

26:43.068 --> 26:47.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Georgia, and there he finds that
his business,
his peanut business, is a
million dollars

26:47.372 --> 26:52.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in debt, that his house is in
need of repair,
and, literally, the forest has
come right

26:52.978 --> 26:55.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up to his back step, their back
step.

26:55.514 --> 26:58.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was kind of this metaphor
for Jimmy
Carter's life.

26:58.617 --> 27:01.220 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How does he navigate through the
thicket?

27:01.253 --> 27:07.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How does he have meaning in his
life, after
he was a one-term, relatively
unpopular president?

27:07.192 --> 27:08.594 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so that was his challenge.

27:08.627 --> 27:10.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And he was in his
mid-50s.

27:10.195 --> 27:11.163 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: He was.

27:11.196 --> 27:12.598 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He was 56.

27:12.631 --> 27:15.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, how did he go
about figuring
out what he would do?

27:15.133 --> 27:19.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: When
you look at
Carter, what you saw was a man
who was -- his

27:19.171 --> 27:24.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
personality, he was very smart,
very ambitious,
and he had a kind of biblical
ethos.

27:24.643 --> 27:29.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, Walter Mondale told me
that Jimmy
Carter said, you know, when this
is all over,

27:29.248 --> 27:30.983 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I want to be a missionary.

27:31.016 --> 27:31.984 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So there's that.

27:32.017 --> 27:34.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And then there was his
presidency.

27:34.219 --> 27:39.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And what you saw in the
presidency, it was
a rough presidency, but he had
this one defining

27:39.057 --> 27:44.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
area, right, Camp David, peace
between Israel
and Egypt.

27:45.030 --> 27:50.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what he did is, he took
those two things
and he created the Carter
Center.

27:50.469 --> 27:55.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Carter Center absolutely
redefined
the post-presidency for everyone
who came

27:55.140 --> 27:56.875 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
behind him.

27:56.909 --> 28:02.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He created this institution
where he could
do freelance diplomacy and other
good works

28:02.447 --> 28:03.749 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
around the world.

28:03.782 --> 28:08.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the Carter Center has
monitored more than
100 elections.

28:08.287 --> 28:10.088 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's won the Nobel Peace Prize.

28:10.122 --> 28:15.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He also kind of got under -- he
was kind of
a burr under the saddle of his
successors.

28:15.661 --> 28:23.168 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
Because of this
peace-at-any-cost type of
ethos, he ended up interfering
in their policies.

28:23.201 --> 28:29.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, under President
Clinton, North
Korea was developing nuclear
weapons, and

28:29.975 --> 28:36.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Carter went over as a private
citizen and
said that economic sanctions
were off the

28:36.348 --> 28:37.316 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
table.

28:37.349 --> 28:38.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He said this on television.

28:38.350 --> 28:40.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Clinton was absolutely
furious.

28:40.519 --> 28:45.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, after the
Jimmy Carter
legacy of building up the Carter
Center, a

28:45.824 --> 28:49.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
couple of presidents later,
along comes Bill
Clinton, very different set of
circumstances.

28:50.028 --> 28:51.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Yes,
absolutely.

28:51.863 --> 28:57.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Bill Clinton also had a
pretty rough landing
when he was the ex-president.

28:57.069 --> 29:02.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On his first day out of office,
he went to
the coffee shop in Chappaqua,
New York, to

29:02.341 --> 29:08.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
get a cup of coffee, and
suddenly he was surrounded
with a phalanx of reporters,
right?

29:08.313 --> 29:13.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he -- they were shouting
questions at
him: Why did you pardon Marc
Rich, the fugitive

29:13.785 --> 29:14.753 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
financier?

29:14.786 --> 29:15.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why did you do that?

29:15.854 --> 29:18.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And suddenly he found himself
completely naked.

29:18.624 --> 29:20.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't have a press office to
protect him.

29:20.525 --> 29:24.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He had no barrier between
himself and the
rest of the world.

29:24.830 --> 29:30.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was a really rough time
for him, made
all the more rough because he
was counting

29:31.003 --> 29:34.506 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on some speeches to help him
with his debt.

29:34.539 --> 29:40.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you remember, he came out of
office with
$12 million in legal fees
because of the impeachment

29:40.579 --> 29:41.546 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
proceedings.

29:41.580 --> 29:43.415 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And he paid a lot to his
lawyers.

29:43.448 --> 29:47.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of those speeches just
disappeared overnight
because of the Marc Rich
controversy, so it

29:47.586 --> 29:49.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was a pretty tough time for him.

29:49.521 --> 29:53.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You wrote, I
think, that Clinton
was described as having given a
lot of thought

29:53.959 --> 29:55.193 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to his post-presidency.

29:55.227 --> 29:56.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Yes,
apparently from
the first...

29:56.862 --> 29:57.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: While he was
president.

29:57.896 --> 29:59.731 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Right.

29:59.765 --> 30:03.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Apparently, from the first day
he was in office,
he was thinking about his
post-presidency.

30:03.602 --> 30:07.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he set up the Clinton
Foundation when
he was still president.

30:07.873 --> 30:10.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so he has -- he had given a
lot of thought
to it.

30:10.976 --> 30:15.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's just those plans were a
little bit delayed
while he had to get through
those first rough

30:15.113 --> 30:17.015 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
months.

30:17.049 --> 30:20.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
the Clinton
Foundation and what it's been
able to accomplish,

30:20.686 --> 30:23.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
compared to Jimmy Carter's work
at the Carter
Center?

30:23.288 --> 30:28.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Well,
the Clinton
Foundation is kind of the Carter
Center on

30:28.393 --> 30:29.995 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
steroids, right?

30:30.028 --> 30:34.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean -- and it reflects Bill
Clinton's personality.

30:34.299 --> 30:39.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when he started this Clinton
Foundation,
it is a global enterprise to do
good.

30:39.805 --> 30:40.772 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

30:40.806 --> 30:42.441 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have done a lot of good.

30:42.474 --> 30:44.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have gotten sugary drinks
out of public
schools.

30:44.810 --> 30:49.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have driven down the price
of AIDS medicine
in Africa.

30:49.247 --> 30:54.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But with the
Clinton Foundation
comes a lot of money.

30:54.286 --> 30:58.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have raised a lot of money,
and then
there were questions about how
that money

30:58.223 --> 31:00.125 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was spent.

31:00.158 --> 31:02.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Yes,
there was questions
about how the money was spent
and whom he

31:02.160 --> 31:06.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
raised the money from, the royal
Saudi family
and Blackwater.

31:06.298 --> 31:11.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's kind of really a lot of
murkiness,
which actually didn't help his
wife in her

31:11.236 --> 31:13.238 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
presidential campaign, of
course.

31:13.271 --> 31:14.973 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There were a lot of questions
about it.

31:15.006 --> 31:21.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, you know, what Bill Clinton
did with
his post-presidency is, he
turned it into

31:21.713 --> 31:24.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a money-making enterprise for
himself.

31:24.649 --> 31:34.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, since 2001, Bill Clinton has
earned $250
million in speaking fees and in
book contracts.

31:34.559 --> 31:38.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As one person said it, being
president is
a really, really good career
move.

31:38.730 --> 31:40.499 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

31:40.532 --> 31:46.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: His successor,
George W. Bush,
comes along, has, of course, his
own set of

31:46.371 --> 31:50.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issues during his presidency,
and approaches
his ex-presidency very
differently.

31:50.876 --> 31:51.943 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Very
differently.

31:51.977 --> 31:54.179 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He was delighted not to be
president.

31:54.212 --> 31:59.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He tells this story that, the
day after he
left the White House, he's down
in Crawford,

31:59.284 --> 32:03.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Texas, and he opens a newspaper,
and he looks
at the news, and he thinks, what
are we going

32:03.488 --> 32:04.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to do about this?

32:04.856 --> 32:08.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then he realizes, I don't
have to do anything
about this.

32:08.293 --> 32:09.995 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is no longer on my watch.

32:10.028 --> 32:15.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, he closes up the papers, he
grabs his
two dogs, drives to the office
and starts

32:15.233 --> 32:17.135 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
writing anecdotes for his book.

32:17.169 --> 32:24.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, he absolutely loved being
away from -- what
I understand, from the everyday
pressures

32:24.576 --> 32:26.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the presidency.

32:26.044 --> 32:29.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And he's been one
of the less
visible former presidents.

32:29.748 --> 32:30.715 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Yes.

32:30.749 --> 32:31.716 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Yes, he has.

32:31.750 --> 32:32.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you
account for that?

32:32.818 --> 32:34.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: I think
it's personality.

32:34.419 --> 32:38.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His speechwriter said that the
reason he seems
content is because he is
content.

32:38.490 --> 32:40.892 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He isn't trying to burnish his
legacy.

32:40.926 --> 32:46.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's unbothered about the
criticism of his
eight years in office, the wars
and the recession

32:46.998 --> 32:48.567 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and all of that.

32:48.600 --> 32:52.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what he does is, he does
the things
that give him meaning and
purpose.

32:52.237 --> 32:58.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's pivoted toward his friends,
toward mountain
biking, toward golfing.

32:58.043 --> 33:01.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Also, he goes to Africa and he
looks in on
the clinics and things like
that.

33:01.813 --> 33:07.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you know what he's really
into right now
is, he's into painting, took it
very seriously.

33:07.219 --> 33:08.353 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He took lessons.

33:08.386 --> 33:11.656 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He does it hours every day, and
now he's painting.

33:11.690 --> 33:16.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's painted war veterans, many
of them wounded,
as a kind of tribute to them.

33:16.761 --> 33:18.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, let's talk
about President
Obama.

33:18.830 --> 33:19.798 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Yes.

33:19.831 --> 33:22.567 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: He's out of
office.

33:22.601 --> 33:28.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's got his own eight-year
legacy, and a
very different set of
circumstances than he

33:28.240 --> 33:29.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
anticipated as he left office.

33:29.808 --> 33:32.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: This
election really
muddied the waters.

33:32.811 --> 33:36.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was a sense that the world
was Barack
Obama's oyster.

33:36.815 --> 33:38.617 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He could do anything he wanted.

33:38.650 --> 33:44.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He could work on gun control or
race relations
or criminal justice reform,
climate change.

33:44.189 --> 33:45.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He could own a basketball team.

33:45.590 --> 33:47.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He could teach law.

33:47.492 --> 33:49.327 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He could do anything he wanted.

33:49.361 --> 33:54.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The day after the election, we
realized that
his opportunities were
circumscribed, at least

33:54.766 --> 34:00.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the beginning, because
there's a Republican
president and Congress who is
actually actively

34:00.739 --> 34:03.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seeking to undo some of his
greatest achievements.

34:03.575 --> 34:10.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what's really interesting
about this time
is, this election actually gave
him a new,

34:10.248 --> 34:16.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unexpected purpose, because the
Clintons are
no longer really the head of the
Democratic

34:16.121 --> 34:17.188 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Party.

34:17.222 --> 34:20.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's the senior statesman in the
Democratic
Party.

34:20.358 --> 34:26.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He knows that he needs to begin
to work on
developing new talent, bringing
the party

34:26.731 --> 34:27.799 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
along.

34:27.832 --> 34:29.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so he's got this short-term
purpose as
well.

34:29.668 --> 34:34.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The other thing
about President
Obama was the importance to him
of family.

34:34.506 --> 34:38.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He talked -- he spoke about
living over the
store, being able to have dinner
every night

34:38.310 --> 34:39.411 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with his daughters.

34:39.444 --> 34:42.714 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that will affect his life
post-presidency.

34:42.747 --> 34:46.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: You
know, Erik Erikson,
the great psychologist, said you
need three

34:46.518 --> 34:47.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
things for midlife.

34:47.686 --> 34:51.389 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You need work, love and play.

34:51.423 --> 34:53.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he has -- he will find
meaningful work.

34:53.792 --> 34:55.260 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And he has play.

34:55.293 --> 35:00.498 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He bodysurfs and plays
basketball and reads
voraciously, and then love.

35:00.532 --> 35:02.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's got a lot of friends, but
he's got his
family.

35:02.067 --> 35:06.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, this was a man who spent
his childhood
kind of without a father.

35:06.938 --> 35:13.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in many ways, he defines
himself more
as a dad and a husband than he
does as a president

35:13.611 --> 35:15.413 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or an ex-president.

35:15.447 --> 35:20.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, kind of one of the -- one of
the things
that people told me is that
leaving the White

35:20.118 --> 35:22.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
House is not going to be
difficult for him.

35:22.721 --> 35:31.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's going to be really
difficult is watching
his children leave the nest.

35:32.030 --> 35:46.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Since the shootings
at Columbine
High School in 1999, there's
been a big rise

35:46.544 --> 35:48.713 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in police stationed at schools.

35:48.747 --> 35:52.317 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There are 44,000 around the
country.

35:52.350 --> 35:57.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's led to concerns over their
role and whether
teenage behavior is sometimes
being inappropriately

35:57.956 --> 35:59.724 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
criminalized.

35:59.758 --> 36:04.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A new analysis of federal civil
rights data
by Education Week finds that
black students

36:04.996 --> 36:09.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are more likely to attend
schools with police
officers present, and they are
three times

36:09.968 --> 36:14.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more likely to be arrested on
campus than
white students.

36:14.105 --> 36:19.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Kavitha
Cardoza with
our partner Education Week has a
report on

36:19.044 --> 36:24.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how the St. Paul public schools
in Minnesota
are revamping their approach.

36:24.315 --> 36:27.619 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is from our weekly series
Making the
Grade.

36:27.652 --> 36:33.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Minnesota, it's
known for
the Vikings, Lake Wobegon, and
being nice.

36:33.992 --> 36:39.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in the past year, a series
of violent
interactions within the St. Paul
school system

36:39.497 --> 36:51.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has taken center stage, school
fights, teacher
assaults, and one incident where
a visiting

36:52.010 --> 36:58.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
student was arrested for
trespassing, all
caught on cell phones and, of
course, widely

36:58.650 --> 37:01.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shared on social media.

37:01.920 --> 37:13.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Teachers threatened to strike,
the superintendent
was fired, and more than 100
students walked

37:13.598 --> 37:15.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out in protest.

37:15.633 --> 37:17.635 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Makkah Abdur Salaam is a senior.

37:17.669 --> 37:20.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAKKAH ABDUR SALAAM, Student:
The truth is,
I don't feel safe around police.

37:20.105 --> 37:22.006 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Like, it's point blank, period.

37:22.040 --> 37:27.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Students like
Saffiyah Al'Aziz
Mohammed (ph) say rocky
police-civilian relations

37:27.579 --> 37:30.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have filtered down to schools
all over the
country.

37:30.548 --> 37:36.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAFFIYAH AL'AZIZ MOHAMMED,
Student: Us seeing
all this police brutality in the
media, and

37:36.588 --> 37:40.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then going to school, and then
your interactions
with school police aren't good,
it's kind

37:40.859 --> 37:42.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of, like, traumatizing a little
bit.

37:42.727 --> 37:48.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Nationwide,
there were nearly
70,000 arrests during the 2013
school year.

37:48.500 --> 37:53.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in most states, black
students are far
more likely to be arrested,
according to an

37:53.938 --> 37:58.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
analysis of federal data by the
Education
Week Research Center.

37:58.910 --> 38:04.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One reason might be that they
are far more
likely to be in schools with
police officers.

38:04.048 --> 38:10.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Laura Olson is trying to change
the relationship
between students and police
officers in St.

38:10.455 --> 38:12.223 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Paul schools.

38:12.257 --> 38:14.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAURA OLSON, Saint Paul Public
Schools: If
students don't feel safe when
they come to

38:14.926 --> 38:17.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
school, they're not going to be
in a position
to learn.

38:17.295 --> 38:20.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: One of the
first things she
did?

38:20.265 --> 38:21.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Change the uniforms.

38:21.933 --> 38:28.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some students expressed that
they felt uncomfortable,
kind of that paramilitary look.

38:28.173 --> 38:35.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, over the summer, instead of
the hard military-style
blue and metal badge, they moved
to a more

38:35.780 --> 38:39.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
soft blue polo shirt with
stitched-on badge.

38:39.117 --> 38:44.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Officers, known
as school
resource officers, are still
armed and carry

38:44.722 --> 38:50.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tasers, but Olson hopes this
softer look makes
them more approachable.

38:50.962 --> 38:52.330 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Another change?

38:52.363 --> 38:56.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Clarify when SRO's should step
in and when
should they step aside.

38:56.501 --> 39:01.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAURA OLSON: We realized that we
had a bit
of a disconnect between what is
perceived

39:01.606 --> 39:05.376 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as behavior and what is criminal
activity.

39:05.410 --> 39:10.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is the line between what
schools handle
and what the SRO handles?

39:10.448 --> 39:12.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And sometimes the lines were a
little blurry.

39:13.017 --> 39:18.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Commander Kevin
Casper has
also increased training for SROs
in areas

